<br>
I never said it was right to do painful experiments on animals. I am against unneccesary pain. But if they are needed for medical research (and I happen to beleive they are, that is only my opinion) Then I do not object to them being used to work towards saving human lives. <br>
<br>
It's not Elitism (funny that you picked that word hehe <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  ). I don't think I am better then any other human being. It's survival of the fittest. I would never condone experimentation on other humans, slavery, anything that was blatantly suggesting, I am better then another member of my race, and therefore I have the right to treat them as inferrior. But do I view animals as inferrior beings to humans, that exist to sustain our lifestyle and make us stronger and healthier? Yea.<br>
<br>
That doesn't mean that I'd condone abusing that power, and responsibility simply because I am a superior being. And that also doesn't mean that I don't respect the things that animals provide for me. Food to nourish me, clothes to keep me warm. And yes, using them to find cures to diseases that effect humans. On this earth, that is the natural order of things. No amount of hypothesizing what would happen if a superior race to us landed on earth and did to us what we did to humans, will disprove the fact that we need animals to live. <br>
<br>
If we aren't leaving animals alone, we are pushing them out of their homes to make space to build our homes. If we aren't driving them out of their homes, we are putting them in zoos for attraction and educational purposes. If we aren't putting them in zoos, we are raising them on farms to be milked, sheared and skinned for clothing, slaughtered for meat, used for their eggs. If we aren't raising them in farms, we are taking them into our homes as obedient, loyal, and friendly companions, and viewed as honorary members of our families. If we aren't taking them into our homes, they are in labs where their bodies are experimented on, and lives sacrificed to cure, heal, save human lives. Where do you draw the line?<br>
<br>
No one on this thread hates animals. I think that is important to remember. We just have different opinions of the limit and extent to which we should use them in our lives. But we do use them. And I couldn't imagine a world where we didn't embrace them the way we do into our civilization. That is why I respect what they provide for us.<br>
<br>
Croneus Titanis<br>
57th Defiler<br>
